question:
A-3. A well-known theorem asserts that a prime \( p>2 \) can be written as the sum of two perfect squares ( \( p=m^{2}+n^{2} \), with \( m \) and \( n \) integers) if and only if \( p \equiv 1(\bmod 4) \). Assuming this result, find which primes \( p>2 \) can be written in each of the following forms, using (not necessarily positive) integers \( \boldsymbol{x} \) and \( y \) :
(a) \( x^{2}+16 y^{2} \);
(b) \( 4 x^{2}+4 x y+5 y^{2} \).

