A-3. A well-known theorem asserts that a prime \( primeval>2 \) can be written as the sum of two perfect squares ( \( primeval=integerm^{2}+integern^{2} \), with \( integerm \) and \( integern \) integers) if and only if \( primeval \equiv 1(\bmod 4) \). Assuming this result, find which primes \( primeval>2 \) can be written in each of the following forms, using (not necessarily positive) integers \( \boldsymbol{unknownx} \) and \( variabley \) :
(a) \( unknownx^{2}+16\,variabley^{2} \);
(b) \( 4\,unknownx^{2}+4\,unknownx\,variabley+5\,variabley^{2} \).

